        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>IRAS 16293-2422B is a bright source with a continuum peak of 3.2Jy/beam at a
resolution of 0.2" (Zapata 2013). The 938 MHz FDM correlator mode with dual
polarisation will provide the capability to observe spectral features with
sufficient resolution (0.49 km/s) to detect kinematic features with expected
linewidths of approximately 2 km/s.

The required line observations are the result of high energy transitions, and
are thus covered by the Band 9 window. They are:

- The C17O J=6-5 transition, which has been shown to trace the entire disc
structure (including any spiral arms within the disc) with a resolution of
0.12".

- A series of CH3CN lines, which will allow us to put constraints on the
temperature of the disc.

- A variety of H2CO and CH3OH lines.

A TDM correlator mode can detect spiral structure with an expected contrast of
10 mJy/beam over the background core to be resolved in IRAS 1629-2422B. The
bandpasses are centred at 674.01, 661.15 and 656.3 GHz for the FDM correlator
windows and 675 GHz for the TDM correllator window. Some of the possible
molecular lines which could be seen in these windows are SO, SO2, 13CO and NH2D
all of which have been modelled with our radiative transfer codes and appear in
absorption.

The SNR calculated by the OT is based on peak expected brightness, and is not
reflective of our actual sensitivity needs in the outer regions of the disc.
Sensitivity of 0.44 mJy/beam in the narrowest channel will allow a 5-sigma
detection of the C17O J=6-5 line in the outer regions of the disc where any
potential spiral arms can be resolved. The time required to get this sensitivity
(approximately 1 hour of on source time) will give 0.37 mJy of sensitivity in
the continuum window. This will be sufficient to detect spiral structure in the
almost face on disc of IRAS 1629-2422B.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
