    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to test planet formation and disc evolution theory by investigating whether very young protoplanetary discs have non-axisymmetric structure that is consistent with global gravitational instabilities. ALMA observations of the young protostar IRAS 16293-2422B will provide high-resolution spatial and kinematic data for direct comparison with state-of-the-art hydrodynamical, chemical and radiative transfer models of protoplanetary discs. If gravitational instabilities are present in young discs, then they will play a fundamental role in mass transport, and may have broad implications for planet and brown dwarf formation, as well as stellar multiplicity.</prp:abstract>
